      "question": "If $\\sin(A - B) = \\frac{1}{2}$ and $\\cos(A + B) = \\frac{1}{2}$, where $0^\\circ < A + B \\le 90^\\circ$ and $A > B$, find $A$ and $B$.",
      "answer": "A = 45^\\circ, B = 15^\\circ",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the angles for which sine is 1/2 and cosine is 1/2.",
          "Solve the resulting linear equations for A and B."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\sin(A-B) = \\sin 30^\\circ \\implies A-B = 30^\\circ. \\cos(A+B) = \\cos 60^\\circ \\implies A+B = 60^\\circ. \\text{Adding the equations, } 2A = 90^\\circ \\implies A = 45^\\circ. \\text{Then } 45^\\circ + B = 60^\\circ \\implies B = 15^\\circ."
      },
